-- PRESS DIGEST - Hong Kong - April 14
-- By Donny Kwok
-- Sun Apr 13, 2014 09:48PM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, April 14 (Reuters) - These are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Monday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST  -- Beijing has left the door open on the possibility of a pan-democrat being allowed to run for chief executive in 2017. But there is no possibility of public nomination of candidates, Hong Kong's lawmakers were told during a meeting with senior mainland officials in Shanghai. (http://link.reuters.com/zab58v) -- The United States looks set to reintroduce annual reports to Congress on political developments in Hong Kong following a plea by the Democratic Party's founding chairman Martin Lee Chu-ming. (http://link.reuters.com/ceb58v) -- Hong Kong's financial services minister has warned market players not to expect the quota under the proposed cross-border stock trading scheme to be increased after it is filled, despite complaints that the cap is too low. (http://link.reuters.com/deb58v)  THE STANDARD -- Both primary and secondary home market sales improved slightly during the weekend. The leader was Cheung Kong Holdings <0001.HK> with its final batch of flats -- all 402 homes -- at Trinity Towers, sold in two weeks. (http://link.reuters.com/heb58v) -- Wing Tai Properties <0369.HK> expects to invest up to HK$710 million in developing the most expensive residential plot in Hong Kong's Sai Wan Ho. (http://link.reuters.com/meb58v)  HONG KONG ECONOMIC JOURNAL  -- Media services group SMI Culture Group Holdings Ltd <2366.HK> said it planned to invest in making 8 to 10 movies this year. One of the movies it has invested in -- American Dreams in China -- recorded 539 million yuan in box office receipts on the mainland.HONG KONG ECONOMIC TIMES  -- CITIC Pacific <0267.HK>, which is expected to announce details of its acquisition of parent assets on April 16, may issue new shares and obtain a syndicated loan to raise capital to finance the deal, according to market sources. Sovereign funds, such as Temasek, may be introduced as strategic investors, they added.